Year 18
1000 lights. An offering to my precious teacher. We keep the fires burning. Forever in my heart we are one. Like an angel, you took me under your wing, protected me, guided me and taught me how to dance in the sky. Not a day goes by without you in my thoughts. 
I send light to you and to all who have lost someone dear to them. May it illuminate the way, cast aside the shadow of fear and doubt, cut through your pain, delusion and darkness like a flaming sword and ease all suffering. 
Until I see your smiling  face again.. Thank you. ཐུགས་རྗེ་ཆེ་། 💎
Om Om Om.
🙏🏽

All of us know Everybody Gets Hurt probably one of the most iconic 90’s hardcore bands from Queens, New York.
Part of #IDSCREW: #Irate #SwornEnemy #TerrorAve #BillyClubSandwich you name it.

Everything on this band is unique Starting for the graffiti wild style logo to the art work all made by Chriss Benetos (@revolt_chrisbeee ) EGH guitarrist.
Also is legendary their apparition’s in Guerrilla Warfare Fanzine and their mosh parts full of Cartwheels staple move of the IDS crew the band is also mentioned in the iconic intro of the song Vendetta by IRATE

But today we are gonna talk about Jessica Pimentel. 
A American Actress born and raised in New York City. She was the vocalist for EGH in the 2000’s for their Japanese tours. Also former member on a few NYHC bands, she played bass in Desolate, guitar in Step 2 Far bass an vocals in New Faith and vocals in Everybody gets hurt. But she’s mostly known for her role on the Netflix Series Orange is the new black. I can’t make this band more unique and different.

She’s currently a member Alekhines Gun and Brujería where she does vocals for both bands.

Also honorable mention to Little Greg (RIP) for creating this amazing band , composing this insanely tough riffs and representing NYHC mosh .

I noticed all these people on TikTok bugging out when using the teenager filter, looking at the more youthful version of themselves and sometimes crying over it.  I was curious and opened up the app only to be hit with a different filter called "bold glamour". Filters are nothing new and beauty filters are quite commonly used but, this filter absolutely broke my heart and made me cry because it didn't just put makeup on me or some fake lashes or give me puppy ears.  It completely took away "MY"  face. Every distinct thing about me. My thin upper lip. My sneaky eye and deep eye color. The bump on my nose that I got from my ancestors. My mismatched eyebrows which grow in completely differently made shockingly clear during the pandemic when I was trying to go all natural with everything (They say eyebrows are sisters not twins but mine are more like cousins 😂). Basically every unique quirky thing about my appearance is gone..... And then I thought... THIS is what we're teaching our young ones. We're showing them that when they look into a mirror, the only way that they will be glamorous and beautiful is if they spend money. Pay as much as you can to take the 'you' out of your face. It made me so so sad. Especially since I have some young little girls who I adore in my life and I can't bear to imagine them seeing themselves ever as less than the perfections that they already are and will continue to be. 
I'm not judging anyone who does things like this to themselves. To each his own and you do whatever makes you happy but we've gotten to this level of boring homogeny where I'm looking at this picture And it could be three or four other people interchangeably. I don't know I just got emotional. I'm having a moment.... 💔
#boldglamourfilter #eraseyourface

Last night was quite a night full of blurry pictures, hugs, big hair, big smiles. And lots and lots of love. You could say it was a bit of a high school reunion because one of my oldest friends got a little bit older. Mercury lounge was definitely not the place to be if you're afraid of kick ass talented women from Brooklyn. 
I don't think there's ever been that many Brooklyn girls in a Manhattan club since 1996. Big big congrats to @lamacchiamusic for blessing us another year with his talent and presence Love you Johnny 2 cakes... I'm pretty sure there will be many many more blurry pictures surfacing today. But I think everyone is still sleeping. 🧿 #threewitches #thescottishplay #familyreunion #afamilyplot

We hit rewind HARD last night. So great to see all these amazing friends come out to celebrate @lamacchiamusic. At one point I looked around the room and realized that I had known some of these people since I was 13 years old. It was also amazing to realize that the same things that we loved and did back when we were kids is what became our lives now. From getting that first guitar on 48th street and recording little songs on a four track, to starring on each other's music videos (remember then BLOOD shoot?) to playing festivals around the world. We did it. We all did it and are doing it. So proud, and happy and thankful and inspired by everyone in this photo. If you don't know you better ask somebody....

The last time I saw Depeche Mode I was coming from a memorial service.
It was the service of one of my dearest, oldest, closest friends and brother Andrew. We had planned to go to that show together. The deal was I would buy the tickets for the first night and he would buy the second night.. Tickets were bought, flights booked But the trip was never made as he passed away suddenly from an agressive cancer and it's complications.. We didn't even get a chance to say goodbye. In fact, We were kind of in a little fight as siblings often have And I didn't answer his last call. That still hurts.
My amazing partner agreed to go with me for the first night and Ironically, painfully, fittingly , Andrew's memorial was on the day of the second show .. the worst day for all New Yorkers, September 11th. At some point, through all the hugs and tears it occurred to me that my jerk Brother still owed me a ticket!! I laughed so freaking hard Because I knew I had to go now. He wouldn't have wanted it any other way and I couldn't think of any other way to honor him and be more New York than going to a concert at Madison square garden on the saddest day ever. Thankfully, a friend helped me get a last minute box seat and I danced and cried and danced and sang and cheered till I lost my voice and my feet were throbbing. Yesterday was no different. I got to see the @depechemode 'Momento Mori' tour last night after coming from a full day of prayers for a funeral service fittingly on the saddest day of the year for most New York metalheads 4/14,  when we lost Peter Steele.
🖤
Thank you David Thank you Martin.
After Temple I went to church.
🖤
Momento Mori, Lama Zopa. 
Peter Steele. Andrew Borden and especially Andy Fletcher... I never thought there'd be a day that I would see Depeche Mode without Fletch
 💔
Momento Mori-  Ngepar Chiwa - 
Death is everywhere 💃💀💃 So live 
And answer your damn phone when someone calls you.

social_posts.post_text:
Paying my respects for the second time in a day to the iconic @andrewlloydwebber show @phantomopera which has been a part of my life for my entire life and is one of the reasons why I do what I do today. I've seen the show almost every year since 1989 sometimes more than once. I've gone with friends, family and by myself. Every time I saw it I found something new. Ive sat in every section from AA 2 (too close) to rear mezz. I know every word, every note, and how each Phantom and Christine sang their parts differently over the years. I grew up with this soundtrack playing constantly in my home and got to play the oveture on violin with my orchestra at Carnegie Hall. I graduated from @theacademyinstagram at the @majestictheatre and stepped on that stage two more times to speak to graduating classes after me. I think I scared the wardrobe department by knowing exactly which outfit belonged to which chorus actor. Last October I got to sing the Christine high notes with real life phantom @raminkarimloo and was later serenaded by him with "Music of the Night". I started every morning drinking from my PTO mug, entered my house with keys on a PTO keychain and stored my guitar picks in a PTO matchox. I still have all these things. I cannot tell you how many countless hours I let myself escape into that world. Iearned every part, every move, learned all the words, learned every dance. Here at the Opera house was A world where people understood me. They knew that box 5 should always be kept empty as per the ghosts instructions. Here they understood the sacrifices that needed to be made for art. They understood that music was sometimes the only bridge of connection when you felt alone and outcast and unseen and hated. Music is love and love is music. 
And the night is full of both when your heart is sad and lonely and heavy and dark. 
We are not merely losing a show on Broadway. I am losing one of my best friends. New York will never be the same without you. 
"Hide your face so the world will never find you. " ,🥀
.
.
#phantom #phantomoftheopera #musicofthenight #phan #andrewlloydwebber #broadway #brodwaybaby #theatergeek

Beautiful photo of Queen and inspiration, Tina Turner performing a Buddhist ritual at her home altar, Studio City, California, 1979. 🙏 A sister in Dharma and a true master of her craft. 
.
#Repost - @nmaahc
For many African Americans, their introduction to the Buddhist faith came with the release of legendary singer Tina Turner’s autobiography, “I, Tina." In her memoir, Turner details her life’s journey and emphasized how reflective Buddhist chanting strengthened her personal resolve. A member of Soka Gakkai International (SGI), Turner embraced Nichiren Daishonin Buddhism that taught self-awareness and the capacity everyone has to “change poison into medicine.” 

Her faith includes morning and evening prayers (gongyo), chanting a mantra (Nam-myoho-renge-kyo), and regular study of Buddhist principles. Turner said of her practice, “The more I studied Buddhist principles, the deeper I dug within myself and cleaned up whatever attitudes or habits were standing in my way. And the more I chanted and aligned my goals with an authentic desire to inspire happiness in others, the more my life began to improve. I credit my spiritual practice with all the positive transformations—from the smallest to the largest—I’ve had in my career and personal life.” 

Turner is among the hundreds of thousands of African Americans who practice this form of Buddhism and work to transform their lives and eliminate suffering through spiritual meditation.

📸 Tina Turner performing a Buddhist ritual at her home altar, Studio City, California, 1979. Photograph by Isaac Sutton. Johnson Publishing Company Archive. Courtesy J. Paul Getty Trust and Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture

Sitting in the hotel room in Helsinki Finland reflecting on how 2 months and 2 days ago I went from a red carpet premiere in Manhattan straight to Tibetan Buddhist Temple in the mountains of Vermont where I was able to complete a promise that I made to my teacher 21 years ago. It was my first time returning to this place since 2008. I sat in group meditation roughly 9-10 hours a day for 12 days Starting our sessions at 8am and finishing around 10pm learning from one of the greatest living masters in all the world. Surrounded by advanced practitioners and monks and nuns helping us every step of the way. This is just a drop of what I could tell you about this and many other retreats I have done. I realize that most of you know me as a crazy NYHC metal head, or some fancy actress, or musician, dancer, a radio DJ, Latina, Brooklyn girl, New Yorker, or that amazing drummer's wife and all of these are true but I remind you to not let conventional appearances fool you. We are all multifaceted and the most important facet in my life is my Buddhist practice. Usually I keep most of it to myself but I want you to know that whatever I do, The art I put out, No matter how unconventional or aggressive, the images I post, even the clothing I choose to wear, it is all with an underlying base rooted in my Buddhist beliefs. I want to bring joy and understanding on how to ease suffering. I want to be the light in the darkness. I made a promise and the first part of it is complete. The second promise was that I would start speaking more openly about my beliefs and how being a Buddhist has changed my mind, heart and life for the better. I'm very excited to share this with you. I believe that many of us have a preconceived idea of what Buddhists are supposed to look like or how they're supposed to act and I'm here to show you that there are many faces and many ways to practice and many ways to be free. Some of us do it quietly at home and some of us scream into microphones 🙏

Thanks to my amazing sister for this special traditional Tibetan dress (Chuba)which I ended up wearing much more than I had planned to during our retreat together. 
.
#tibetanbuddhism #gelug #lerung #100000

Thank you to everyone for the outpouring of well wishes on my solar return. This photo here captures flawlessly the whirlwind these past 12 months have been and brought more blessings than I can even count. Travel all around the world. A play where I had a dream role. A New streaming show (which I currently can't promote due to the current Screen Actors Guild strike) and working on a show that's taken me 10 years to get on. Working on several musical projects with people I have admired my whole life. A new home. Making new friends and reconnecting with old ones. Giving the keynote address at my alma mater graduation ceremony. More love than I could dream of from my wonderful partner. Having a chance to sit at the feet of some of the greatest living Tibetan Buddhist Masters as well as accomplishing and milestone meditation retreat in the mountains of Vermont fulfilling at 21-year promise. Although I'd be lying to say that it all came easy, I am moved to tears reading all of your wonderful messages of love and encouragement.
From the bottom of my heart thank you, thank you, thank you all for making this day and every day so very special!
I'm so excited to see what this new chapter will bring And if you find it in your heart and pocket, please donate to my fundraiser. We are still taking donations

You most probably have been mentally, verbally, or physically harmed more than once in your life. If you can remember all of those harmful things that happened to you, without having any harmful thoughts towards those who harmed you, that is forgiveness.

Nobody is denying what you had experienced. Nobody is denying that the other person committed a harmful action towards you. What that person did to you, will have future karmic consequences for them. How you respond, will have future karmic consequences for you. Please, for the benefit of yourself, and for all other beings, stop perpetuating this harmful karmic cycle, and respond with forgiveness. 

~ Chamtrul Rinpoche

HAPPY DAKINI DAY!!!! Especially to all my Vajra family who participate in this especially special VY day.
Dakini Day is considered one of the
auspicious days in the lunar calendar and falls on the 25th day of each lunar month. But this particular celebration happens only once a year. It is a powerful day for us to contemplate the qualities of the divine feminine, practice meditation, engage in positive action and make offerings. Dakini in Sanskrit, Khandro in Tibetan, literally means “sky dweller” or “sky dancer,” and is the most sacred aspect of the feminine principle in Tibetan Buddhism, embodying both humanity and divinity in feminine form. Ultimately, all women are seen as some kind of dakini manifestation."A very sharp, brilliant, wisdom mind that is uncompromising, honest with a little bit of wrath" 🩴💎💃🌫️
Love to you all,
